ðŸ“˜ Topic 1: SELECT and FROM
SELECT column1, column2 FROM table_name;

Q1.1: Retrieve all columns from the students table.
ðŸ‘‰ SELECT * FROM students;

Q1.2: Retrieve only the name and age of all students from the students table.
ðŸ‘‰ SELECT name, age FROM students;


ðŸ“˜ Topic 2: WHERE Clause
SELECT * FROM table_name WHERE condition;

Q2.1: Find all students whose age is more than 18.
ðŸ‘‰ SELECT * FROM students WHERE age > 18;

Q2.2: Get employees from the employees table whose department is 'Sales'.
ðŸ‘‰ SELECT * FROM employees WHERE department = 'Sales';


ðŸ“˜ Topic 3: ORDER BY
SELECT * FROM table_name ORDER BY column_name ASC|DESC;

Q3.1: List all students ordered by age.
ðŸ‘‰ SELECT * FROM students ORDER BY age;

Q3.2: Show all products from the products table ordered by price in descending order.
ðŸ‘‰ SELECT * FROM products ORDER BY price DESC;


ðŸ“˜ Topic 4: LIMIT and DISTINCT
SELECT DISTINCT column_name FROM table_name;
SELECT * FROM table_name LIMIT number;

Q4.1: Get the first 5 employees from the employees table.
ðŸ‘‰ SELECT * FROM employees LIMIT 5;

Q4.2: Get first 2 employees from the employees table after leaving first 3.
ðŸ‘‰ SELECT * FROM employees LIMIT 3,2;

Q4.3: Find all distinct departments in the employees table.
ðŸ‘‰ SELECT DISTINCT department FROM employees;


ðŸ“˜ Topic 5: LIKE Operator
The LIKE operator is used for pattern matching using:
% â†’ matches zero or more characters
_ â†’ matches a single character
SELECT * FROM table_name WHERE column LIKE 'pattern';

Q5.1: Get all customers whose name starts with 'A'.
ðŸ‘‰ SELECT * FROM customers WHERE name LIKE 'A%';

Q5.2: Find all books where the title contains the word "Java".
ðŸ‘‰ SELECT * FROM library WHERE title LIKE '%Java%';


ðŸ“˜ Topic 6: Basic Arithmetic in SELECT
You can perform calculations inside the SELECT clause.
SELECT column, column * 2 AS new_column FROM table_name;

Q6.1: Show the price of all products and also display double the price as double_price.
ðŸ‘‰ SELECT name, price, price * 2 AS double_price FROM products;

Q6.2: Get employees names and their yearly salary (salary * 12).
ðŸ‘‰ SELECT name, salary, salary * 12 AS yearly_salary FROM employees;


ðŸ“˜ Topic 7: Aliases (AS keyword)
AS is used to rename columns or tables temporarily in a result set.
SELECT column_name AS alias_name FROM table_name;

Q7.1: Select student names as Student_Name.
ðŸ‘‰ SELECT name AS Student_Name FROM students;

Q7.2: Select product name and price, but rename price as Cost.
ðŸ‘‰ SELECT name, price AS Cost FROM products;
